Let's denote this population as \( P \). For Alphaville, the population changes over three years as follows: - Decreased by 2.9% in 1996: \( P \times (1 - 0.029) \) - Increased by 8.9% in 1997: \( P \times (1 - 0.029) \times (1 + 0.089) \) - Increased by 6.9% in 1998: \( P \times (1 - 0.029) \times (1 + 0.089) \times (1 + 0.069) \) For Betaville, the population increased by \( r \% \) each year: \( P \times \left(1 + \frac{r}{100}\right)^3 \) Since the populations are equal at the end of 1998, we equate the two expressions: \[ (1 - 0.029) \times (1 + 0.089) \times (1 + 0.069) = \left(1 + \frac{r}{100}\right)^3 \] Calculating the left-hand side: \[ 0.971 \times 1.089 \times 1.069 \approx 1.13038 \] Taking the cube root of 1.13038 to find \( 1 + \frac{r}{100} \): \[ \sqrt[3]{1.13038} \approx 1.0417 \] Thus, \[ 1 + \frac{r}{100} \approx 1.0417 \implies \frac{r}{100} \approx 0.0417 \implies r \approx 4.17 \] Rounding to one decimal place, the value of \( r \) is \(\boxed{4.2}\).
